metadata.name: War #15
metadata.description:
"War" is a song written and performed by American soul musician Edwin Starr. It was released as a single in 1970 and became a huge commercial success, reaching number one on the Billboard Hot 100 chart in the United States and selling over three million copies worldwide. The song is known for its powerful lyrics and urgent message against war and violence, with the refrain "War, huh, yeah / What is it good for / Absolutely nothing" becoming one of the most memorable and iconic lines in popular music history. "War" has been covered by numerous artists and has been featured in various media, including films and television shows.

- hit 'p' for .png export
- hit 's' for .svg export

metadata.name: looking through a glass #106
metadata.description:
or life is a colorful mess
or not your usual generative forest

this art project continues the path that 'life is a (beautiful) mess' began with the representation of our lives using drawing lines that make repetitive patterns
as life develops, we look at it through the glass of our unique existence. every event, emotion and thought we experience stain our personal glass and conditions our regard towards the world that surrounds us
the cercles in every composition, represents that glass that we all have between us and the world, and the movement of the lines under it, life developing as we observe it
or it's just another figurative generative art project, as you wish...

10 different palettes
over 30 different color pens
single or multiple color glasses or cercles option
press [1], [2], [3], [4] keys to multiply resolution and reload the piece
press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the drawing
doubleclick the mouse to resume the drawing

metadata.name: The Geometry of Rain #7
metadata.description:
An artwork co-created by Chris Wallace and GPT-4 exploring the relationship between the geometric shapes and the rain, highlighting the intersection of mathematical precision and organic fluidity. 

Written in p5.js, this artwork was created through a process of trial-and-error prompting ChatGPT's AI to make adjustments to the code. In some cases, code needed to be written manually to implement features like color schemes (hat tip to Bruce from Studio Yorktown), fxhash's preview and attributes, as well as some aesthetic changes that ChatGPT is unable to visualize and alter itself. GPT-4 also titled this work and wrote the first sentence of the description.

Press 's' on your keyboard to save a PNG locally.

metadata.name: Charcoal Seeds #361
metadata.description:
As a fundamental element derived from organic matter, charcoal happens to be at the core of all life forms. It is also the tool for artists that dates back to the most ancient times. 
By using charcoal as the the primary medium for the exhibition ‘Organic Matr’ (and resulting series of physical pieces created in collaboration with Brooklyn-based lab ArtMatr), the works creates bonds between technology and the rawest tool that was touched by the human hand, and highlights how the cycle of life is also the cycle of regeneration of matter.

Since the generative process _that uses programming code and the intervention of randomness_ was used to design the physical pieces, the long-form generative series Charcoal Seeds is a natural way to seamlessly extend back into the digital realm the ideas of matter and physicality, while showing the elements at work in the creation process. 
In each iteration a virtual seed will encapsulates the essence of organic forms and patterns. The graphic style itself tries to convey the organic feeling of tools and materials such as chalk, ink, paintbrushes. 


—— 

- "Charcoal Seeds" offers a WYSIWYG experience : by deriving the randomness from the minter’s wallet address, it is guaranteed that what you see onscreen after adjusting the params will be your actual NFT. 
However, we wanted to allow the possibility of getting some rare features. By selecting "random" for the Format or the Paper color, you will get a chance to mint a Pink or a Back background, or have a Wide Landscape format. Beware : this will break the WYSIWYG ( but it will keep your params settings safe ) 

- As usual, the project is plottable : press [s] in live mode to generate a SVG file suited for pen plotters.

- By adding a ‘scale’ parameter in the live URL, you can generate a higher resolution image. The scale ranges from 1 to 10 with a default value of 3.

metadata.name: Hatchet: Kagami #6
metadata.description:
Hatchet: Kagami (鏡) is the third piece in Hatchet; a generative art series that hatches an arrangement of segmented polygons generated via a Voronoi diagram. Kagami (Japanese for 'mirror') arranges it's polygons in reflected symmetry, creating patterns reminiscent of kaleidoscopes and snowflakes. Mixed color palettes alternate between reflections to incorporate a level of asymmetry. As opposed to previous Hatchet pieces, the chance of generating a light and dark background is equal.

All pieces in Hatchet are composed to emulate the aesthetic of colored pencils on paper. Each piece is capable of exporting its hatch lines as a well-labeled SVG document. This will allow collectors interested in plotting to create physical renditions of their iteration.

The following key-press actions are supported on the token:
- 'r': Animate the erasure and re-drawing of the hatch lines.
- 's': Export the SVG document describing the arrangement of hatch lines.

metadata.name: Keep On #129
metadata.description:
One year ago, I published my first Fx(hash) work, "Finding my way". This piece marks its anniversary, and is intended as a THANK YOU to all the people that collected my works. 

It is based on the same algorithm as "Finding my way", i.e. a line growth animated process based on Substrate (Jared Tarbell, 2003) guided by dynamically changing vector fields made with trigonometric functions, but it uses different palettes, more vector fields, and a few more tweakings of the algorithm parameters.

The original piece was intended to symbolise a person's process of finding her/his way. Upon further reflections on the result, I think it more as representing a community process. So here is my wish for the Fx(hash) community, let's keep on finding our way.   

In what now could become a tradition, I've stolen again a palette from the beautiful work of Iskra Velitchkova.

Implemented using various packages from thi.ng/umbrella by Karsten Schmidt, AKA Toxi

metadata.name: Anarchy #84
metadata.description:
"Anarchy" aims to pay tribute to the Impressionist masters and explore the interplay between randomness and control. My goal was to capture the bold use of color and the fleeting nature of light and movement that is so characteristic of the Abstract Impressionist style. 

This piece uses a total of 12 color palettes, each one inspired by a different Impressionist painter. Some artists have two palette variations, while others only have one.

I wanted to create something that was unique and that would reflect my own visual emotions while also paying homage to the artists that inspire me. "Anarchy" is part of my exploration of the relationship between randomness and intention, and a celebration of the enduring legacy of the Impressionist masters.

Made by wandurz using p5.js 
January 2023

metadata.name: Ecce Gratum #66
metadata.description:
"Ecce Gratum" is a symphony of colors and lines, a visual work that sings to the soul. The strokes of the brush are bold and confident, yet gentle and loving, like the notes of a symphony. The title, "Ecce Gratum", translates to "Behold the pleasing", and as you gaze upon this art, it is impossible not to be moved by its beauty and wonder. This painting is a celebration of life, a reminder to embrace the present and to find joy in the simple things. It is a call to look beyond the surface, to see the beauty in the world around us, and to let our hearts sing

[S] on live view to save a png

metadata.name: Euclid's Networks #22
metadata.description:
Each node randomly generated by the code and each node connected to the nearest one.

Distances between each nodes are calculated by using Euclidean Distances Formula (d =√[(x2 – x1)2 + (y2 – y1)2]).

Each Euclid's Networks number of nodes between 30 to 300. There are 43 color sets in total.
